entry.title: [views] Ensure modal constrained windows are visible on-screen
entry.content:
This CL updates UpdateModalDialogPosition() code to ensure

constrained dialogs and their parent windows remain visible

when shown.



The modal dialog may not be user-visible in the case where

1. The transient parent is not visible on-screen

2. The dialog was repositioned outside the bounds of its

transient parent.



Many platforms will clip transient children to the bounds of

the parent so it is necessary that the constrained window

remain within the bounds of the parent to avoid rendering the

window unresponsive when dialog controls become inaccessible.



In the case the transient parent itself is partially or

completely off-screen it is necessary to reposition it back

into the screen's user-visible work area. This is necessary

as otherwise the dialog may end up positioned off-screen

similarly makes the dialog controls inaccessible and

renders the window unresponsive.



Bug: 1341530

entry.title: Multiplanar: Fix GMBVideoFramePool to set external sampler
entry.content:
With legacy multiplanar shared images, for NV12 and P010 formats

GpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool creates single shared image with

DEFAULT buffer plane and goes through external sampler path for

when kMultiPlaneSoftwareVideoSharedImages feature is disabled.



Currently, for new multiplanar shared images, we don't set external

sampler for this client so that the service side samples textures

per plane instead of preferring external sampler through the driver

which causes video playback issues on certain ChromeOS devices.



This change updates the path for new multiplanar shared images

to also prefer external sampler on these ozone based platforms to keep

the paths similar.

entry.title: [Autofill] Fire AskForValuesToFill() on non-click focus on contenteditable
entry.content:
Triggering AskForValuesToFill() on any focus change into a

contenteditable fixes two issues -- and in both cases, it's a hack:



1. AutofillDriverRouter assumes that any messages sent from the browser

to the renderer refer to forms that have previously been sent the

other way. That's not necessarily the case for events triggered

from the context menu.

Triggering AskForValuesToFill() avoids this. It still needs to be

checked if the event is arrives in the browser early enough.



2. When left-clicking into a nested contenteditables, AutofillAgent's

AutofillAgent::HandleFocusChangeComplete() is called with

focused_node_was_last_clicked == false. That seems wrong.



This needs followup work because triggering AskForValuesToFill() on

right clicks, for example, is not desirable.

entry.title: [AssistData] Add histograms to track when max timeout or nodes is exceeded
entry.content:
This CL continues the work to add more tracking for accessibility

snapshots on Android, and their failure rates / failure reasons.



With this CL we add three more types of failures to the enum of possible

AXTree snapshot failure reasons. We consider the case where the max

number of nodes is met, the timeout is reached, or both. We create a new

ax_error_types.h file with the possible types of serialization errors.

We add a new optional parameter to the SerializeChanges method of the

ax_tree_serializer, which when populated will return the error type of

the given serialization call (if one occurs). The possible error types

are max nodes reached, timeout reached, or both. We treat the enum as

a bitmask for convenience.



We include a unit test in the Java-side code that makes a tree much

larger than the max node limit and verifies that the snapshot only

includes a partial tree.

entry.title: Introduce reserved.top_navigation_start/commit.
entry.content:
Automatic beacons currently have one supported beacon type:

reserved.top_navigation. This fires when a navigation commits. There's a

need to expand this to support beacons both at navigation start and

navigation commit. This CL deprecates reserved.top_navigation in favor

of 2 new beacons: reserved.top_navigation_start and

reserved.top_navigation_commit. The deprecation is done in order to have

a more consistent naming convention.



To support multiple automatic beacon types, each beacon type gets its

own automatic beacon data. This is stored in a hash map in the fenced

frame config, using the event type as the key and the

AutomaticBeaconInfo struct as the value.



The event type for automatic beacons is now stored as an enumerated

type. This makes it simpler to track supported automatic beacon types.



This CL refactors automatic beacon tests to support tracking multiple

messages. The automatic-beacon-store.py endpoint uses a hash of the

message to store a beacon, and then the test passes in the message

string to be hashed when checking for the existence of the message.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Fix missing shortcut signals for docs
entry.content:
The shrortcut provider skips ML signals for docs.

The other local providers, HUP, HQP, and bookmarks, don't skip docs.

The doc provider also doesn't write signals.



So we end up with some documents (those from SP and DP) having no

signals; Some docs (those from HQP, HUP, and BK) have all their signals;

and some docs (those that were deduped) have partial signals - e.g. have

history typed count but no shortcut count.



This is bad because:

- inconsistent scoring = inconsistent ML quality,

- many of the cases where we've experienced bad ML quality and tried

looking at the debug data to figure out why would be solved if the

shortcut signals had not been missing



Luckily, this doesn't affect most consumers since docs are enterprise

only. Unfortunately, this does effect us a lot, since we have a lot of

docs, making dogfooding and judging ML quality difficult.



Simply starting to add signals to shortcut provider docs might be

sufficient for now. Then most docs will have signals. Docs from the doc

provider will continue missing signals, but that's because they really

have no signals rather than because they had signals that we threw away

(like we're doing for shortcut docs).



I wonder how we'll eventually start blending in document provider docs;

even if we do figure out some set of signals we can compute for them,

the difference in signals will mean the ML model will be able to clearly

identify which provider the docs are from and could therefore get

provider bias.



We'll also need to change the model training to not ignore SP docs.

Though that's probably not critical since most of the training data is

from consumers who won't have docs.



This change is feature guarded.

entry.title: viz: Allow SurfaceRanges with distinct embed tokens and same FrameSinkId
entry.content:
SurfaceRange currently requires that if the start/end SurfaceIds belong

to the same FrameSink, they should have the same embed token.



This does not hold true when navigating between 2 same-process

RenderFrames with RenderDocument enabled. This is because when sharing

the compositor the 2 widgets use the same FrameSinkId but the new

RenderFrame gets assigned a new embed token for its SurfaceIds. The

SurfaceRange then needs to have 2 Surfaces with the same FrameSinkId

but different embed tokens, so the old RenderFrame's content can be

used as a fallback until the new RenderFrame draws its first frame.

entry.title: FilePathWatcher: Synchronously start watching on Mac
entry.content:
This CL includes two key changes:



1) Moves all manipulation of the event stream (start, stop, etc)

to the sequence the FilePathWatcher lives on



Prior to this CL, the event stream was manipulated on the dispatch

queue. This does not appear to have been necessary. Moving the stream

manipulation to the sequence the FilePathWatcher lives on allows the

event stream to be started synchronously, from the Watch() method



2) Use kFSEventStreamEventIdSinceNow



Prior to this CL, the event stream was started via async dispatch in

the Watch() method. FSEventsGetCurrentEventId() was used to

synchronously get the ID of the most recent (system-wide) event, to

ensure that any changes between when Watch() returned and when the

stream asynchronously started would be played back as historical

events. See the documentation of the sinceWhen field here:

https://developer.apple.com/documentation/coreservices/1443980-fseventstreamcreate



Since the stream is now started synchronously,

kFSEventStreamEventIdSinceNow is sufficient for ensuring that all

changes after Watch() returns are noticed



Note that creating a stream with kFSEventStreamEventIdSinceNow will

no longer fire a "history done" event shortly after stream creation.

Any callers which relied on the this behavior may break.

See the documentation here:

https://developer.apple.com/documentation/coreservices/kfseventstreameventflaghistorydone

entry.title: [TTFPassGen] Fix crash on PasswordGenerationControllerImpl::OnTouchToFillForGenerationDismissed
entry.content:
The crash happens because of the failing check

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/password_manager/android/password_generation_controller_impl.cc;l=373;drc=c177416839ec7a3fe2fe6e91a7e8e519248f96bd;bpv=0;bpt=1?q=password_generation_controller_im&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc.

The problem here is that the call touch_to_fill_generation_controller_.reset() in

PasswordGenerationControllerImpl::HideBottomSheetIfNeeded() causes

PasswordGenerationControllerImpl::OnTouchToFillForGenerationDismissed()

to be called. And because

PasswordGenerationControllerImpl::HideBottomSheetIfNeeded() resets the

TTF state to none before calling the reset, the check fails.

The solution provided in this CL prevents the reciprocate

OnTouchToFillForGenerationDismissed call.
